{"id":"hart","term":"Hart","source":"Easton's Bible Dictionary (M.G. Easton, 1897)","html":"<p>(Heb. ‘ayal), a stag or male deer. It is ranked among the clean animals (<a class=\"ref\" data-ref=\"Deuteronomy 12:15\">Deut. 12:15</a>; <a class=\"ref\" data-ref=\"Deuteronomy 14:5\">14:5</a>; <a class=\"ref\" data-ref=\"Deuteronomy 15:22\">15:22</a>), and was commonly killed for food (<a class=\"ref\" data-ref=\"1 Kings 4:23\">1 Kings 4:23</a>). The hart is frequently alluded to in the poetical and prophetical books (<a class=\"ref\" data-ref=\"Isaiah 35:6\">Isa. 35:6</a>; <a class=\"ref\" data-ref=\"Song of Solomon 2:8\">Cant. 2:8</a>, <a class=\"ref\" data-ref=\"Song of Solomon 2:9\">9</a>; <a class=\"ref\" data-ref=\"Lamentations 1:6\">Lam. 1:6</a>; <a class=\"ref\" data-ref=\"Psalms 42:1\">Ps. 42:1</a>).</p>\n\u0000","refs":["Deuteronomy 12:15","Deuteronomy 14:5","Deuteronomy 15:22","1 Kings 4:23","Isaiah 35:6","Song of Solomon 2:8","Song of Solomon 2:9","Lamentations 1:6","Psalms 42:1"]}